---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
	title="Coverage & Antennas"
	description="Learn how LoRa mesh coverage works in Madison, how to maximize your node's range, and which antennas to use."
>
	<div class="container">
		<section class="section" style="padding-top: 2rem;">
			<h1>Coverage &amp; Antennas</h1>
			<p>
				LoRa (Long Range) radio operates with surprising reach on very low power &mdash; but range depends
				heavily on your antenna, height, and terrain. This page explains how coverage works in Madison and
				how to get the most out of your node.
			</p>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- How LoRa coverage works -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>How LoRa Coverage Works</h2>
			<p>
				LoRa uses a spread-spectrum modulation technique on the 915 MHz ISM band (in North America) that
				allows signals to reach far further than Wi-Fi or Bluetooth. In ideal conditions, a node placed in
				an elevated location can span <strong>10–30 miles</strong>. A node sitting on a desk indoors may
				only reach a few blocks.
			</p>

			<div class="card-grid">
				<div class="card">
					<span class="card-icon">📶</span>
					<h3>Line of Sight</h3>
					<p>
						LoRa performs best when there's an unobstructed path between nodes. Hills, buildings, and
						dense trees all reduce range. Even a few feet of extra elevation can dramatically improve
						coverage.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<span class="card-icon">🏙️</span>
					<h3>Urban Environments</h3>
					<p>
						In a city like Madison, buildings degrade range significantly. Most nodes can reliably
						reach 0.5–3 miles urban, or 2–10 miles from a rooftop or elevated location.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<span class="card-icon">🔁</span>
					<h3>Mesh Relaying</h3>
					<p>
						The power of mesh is that each node forwards messages for others. Even if two nodes can't
						see each other directly, they can communicate through intermediate nodes in the network.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<span class="card-icon">☀️</span>
					<h3>Weather &amp; Season</h3>
					<p>
						LoRa range is relatively immune to rain but Wisconsin's terrain and foliage density in
						summer can reduce effective range. Winter (bare trees) often improves coverage noticeably.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Madison-specific notes -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Coverage in the Madison Area</h2>
			<p>
				Madison's geography is helpful for mesh networking. The isthmus between the two lakes creates
				natural elevation gradients, and the surrounding hills and bluffs can support nodes that cover large
				portions of the city from a single location.
			</p>

			<div class="steps">
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">💡</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Best placement: rooftops and upper floors</h3>
						<p>
							Nodes placed on rooftops or in upper-floor windows dramatically outperform
							ground-level placements. Even getting above the treeline makes a meaningful
							difference. If you can see the Capitol dome from your location, you likely have
							excellent coverage potential.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">💡</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Gaps in coverage</h3>
						<p>
							Currently the network is thinner on Madison's west and east sides, and in many
							surrounding towns. If you're in Fitchburg, Monona, Middleton, Sun Prairie, or Verona
							— you're in a great position to add needed coverage.
							<a href="https://discord.gg/fd3JUZc2CN" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
								>Ask on Discord</a
							>
							for the current coverage map.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">💡</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Check existing nodes first</h3>
						<p>
							Before setting up a new node, try turning one on and seeing if you connect to any
							existing nodes nearby. Meshtastic users can view live node maps at
							<a href="https://meshmap.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
								>meshmap.net</a
							>. MeshCore users can check with the community in our Discord.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Antennas -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Choosing an Antenna</h2>
			<p>
				The stock antenna that comes with most LoRa radios is adequate for portable use but a significant
				upgrade is available for fixed nodes. Here are the main types:
			</p>

			<div class="card-grid">
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Stock Stub Antenna</h3>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">~2 dBi gain</p>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem;">
						The small antenna included with most radios. Fine for portable use or to see if nodes are
						nearby. <strong>Not recommended for fixed nodes</strong> — replace with any of the options below.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Whip / Fiberglass Omni</h3>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">3–6 dBi gain</p>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem;">
						A good general-purpose upgrade. Sends signal in all horizontal directions equally. Great
						for nodes that need to connect to neighbors on multiple sides. Look for N-type or
						SMA-connector models designed for 915 MHz.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Yagi / Directional</h3>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">8–15+ dBi gain</p>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem;">
						Focuses signal in one direction. Very useful for long-distance point-to-point links (e.g.,
						bridging between neighborhoods). Not ideal as the only antenna on a relay node.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Magnetic Mount / Mobile</h3>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">2–5 dBi gain</p>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem;">
						Designed for vehicles. The metal car roof acts as a ground plane and boosts performance.
						Great for mobile nodes used while driving around Madison.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div
				class="card"
				style="margin-top: 1.5rem; background-color: oklch(22% 0.06 232.69); border-color: var(--clr-primary-darker);"
			>
				<h3 style="color: var(--clr-primary);">⚡ Quick upgrade recommendation</h3>
				<p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
					For most fixed home nodes, swap the stock antenna for a <strong
						>3–5 dBi 915 MHz omni antenna</strong
					>
					with an appropriate SMA or N-type connector. The Taoglas FXP73, Linx ANT-916-CW-RCI, and various
					no-name fiberglass options on Amazon all work well for $10–25. Make sure you buy one rated for <strong
						>915 MHz</strong
					> — not 868 MHz (European) or 433 MHz.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Antenna cables and connectors -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Cables, Adapters &amp; Placement</h2>

			<div class="steps">
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">1</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Keep coax cable short</h3>
						<p>
							RF signal is lost in coax cable. Use the shortest cable possible — ideally under 10
							feet for low-cost RG174/RG316 coax. If you need a long run, use higher-quality
							LMR-200 or LMR-400 cable to reduce loss, or consider mounting the radio close to the
							antenna and using a long USB/power cable instead.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">2</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Common connectors</h3>
						<p>
							Most small LoRa boards use <strong>U.FL / IPEX</strong> or <strong>RP-SMA</strong> connectors.
							Many outdoor fiberglass antennas terminate in <strong>N-type</strong>. Be sure to
							check your specific radio's connector type before buying an antenna or pigtail.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">3</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Vertical polarization</h3>
						<p>
							Mount your antenna vertically (pointing straight up). Both ends of a link should use
							the same polarization — mixing vertical and horizontal can cost you 20+ dB of signal
							loss.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">4</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Windows vs. exterior</h3>
						<p>
							A node inside a window loses some signal through the glass and frame. An antenna
							mounted outside on a pole or eave is always better. If running a cable outside is not
							possible, place the node in the highest window facing the most open direction.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<section class="section">
			<h2>Want help with your setup?</h2>
			<p>
				Coverage and RF questions are a common topic in our Discord. Members can help with antenna
				selection, placement ideas, and tell you whether existing nodes are likely in range of your
				location.
			</p>
			<a
				href="https://discord.gg/fd3JUZc2CN"
				target="_blank"
				rel="noopener noreferrer"
				class="btn btn-primary"
			>
				Ask in Discord &rarr;
			</a>
		</section>
	</div>
</Layout>
